<h2>The Question</h2>
<p>
  Can Web Everything add an <strong>AI-assisted translation</strong> capability — source-locale MF2
  catalog → target-locale catalogs on the
  <a href="/protocols/#protocol-localization">Localization protocol</a> — without it becoming a
  standard, and without leaking a model/SDK into <code>@webeverything</code>?
  <a href="/backlog/664-ai-assisted-translation-as-a-plateau-service-on-device-floor/">#664</a> answers
  yes, by applying two already-settled rulings rather than re-opening them.
</p>

<h2>Recommendation (at a glance)</h2>
<ul class="text-sm text-gray-600 list-disc pl-5">
  <li><strong>The capability is a Plateau service, not a standard.</strong> Translation is an
    <em>implementation</em> capability → by the vision-is-a-service ruling
    (<a href="/backlog/475/">#475</a>) it lives in the served-product layer and the WE project consumes
    it through a <strong>thin swappable client seam</strong>. Only the produced catalog reaches the
    standard; <em>how</em> it was produced is invisible. <em>(no-leakage.)</em></li>
  <li><strong>The one durable @webeverything edge is the verification</strong> — now codified in the
    Localization protocol contract: a produced catalog is <em>provably-conformant</em>. This is the
    <a href="/backlog/089/">#089</a> "AI proposes, the standard verifies" loop applied to translation.</li>
  <li><strong>Pricing is not re-opened.</strong> The linear-cost rule
    (<a href="/backlog/488/">#488</a>) already settled it: on-device is the bundled default/floor;
    hosted-API + BYO-key is the metered bridge. Translation is an <em>even cleaner</em> on-device fit
    than vision — the browser ships an on-device Translator / Language-Detector API and small open MT
    models (NLLB-200, MADLAD-400, Opus-MT) run locally.</li>
</ul>

<h2>The conformance contract (the standard-side half)</h2>
<p>
  The verification that makes ours provably-conformant where incumbents (Lokalise / Phrase / DeepL)
  are merely plausible — model-free, published, the only piece eligible to live in
  <code>@webeverything</code>. A produced target catalog verifies that it:
</p>
<ul class="text-sm text-gray-600 list-disc pl-5">
  <li>preserves every <strong>MF2 placeholder / selector / markup part</strong> from the source — no
    dropped <code>{$count}</code>, no broken <code>.match</code> plural arms;</li>
  <li>covers the target locale's <strong>CLDR plural / gender categories</strong> (ICU categories
    present);</li>
  <li>leaves <strong>no untranslated-but-claimed keys</strong> and <strong>no placeholder-arity
    drift</strong>.</li>
</ul>
<p>
  The model lives in the Plateau service (production); the gate lives in the standard (verification).
  The executable harness is a <em>deferred build</em> that lands when the Localization protocol
  graduates from <code>concept</code>.
</p>

<h2>Open questions (translation-specific — research, not blocking forks)</h2>
<ul class="text-sm text-gray-600 list-disc pl-5">
  <li><strong>On-device quality per locale-pair</strong> — which pairs clear the conformance bar today
    (browser Translator API + NLLB/MADLAD class) and which need the hosted bridge? Per-pair graduation
    benchmark on the #488 cadence, not a one-time reject.</li>
  <li><strong>Distillation dataset</strong> — does the <code>(source, target, verdict)</code> corpus
    train an on-device fine-tune the way the #488 vision verdict cache does (the platform-reinforcing
    loop)?</li>
  <li><strong>Markup survival</strong> — catalog- vs message-level invocation, and how MF2 markup parts
    survive a model that wasn't trained MF2-aware (pre/post placeholder-masking inside the client seam).</li>
</ul>

